    "recap_headline": "University of Washington",
    "recap_text": "LOS ANGELES \u2013\nJackson Hotchkiss\nled the Huskies to their best offensive output of the weekend in Southern California as the Huskies dropped the final game of the series to No. 13 USC 14-4.\nWashington moves to 9-14 and 4-5 in Big Ten play.\nJackson Hotchkiss\ngot things started early, launching his first home run of the day in the very first at bat of the game. On a 3-1 count, the sophomore smoked the ball 115 miles per hour off the bat to left field, sending the ball 419 feet.\nUSC responded in the bottom of the first, scoring five runs to take the lead.\nThe Huskies found another run when Hotchkiss led off the third inning. This time, he took a 2-1 count pitch to left again, bringing his season home run total to six.\nWashington's left fielder is averaging one home run every two games.\nThe Huskies added a run in the fourth on a\nMic Paul\nRBI triple, scoring Alex Pearson from first. In the fifth,\nDaniel Porras\ndrove in\nBraeden Terry\nwith an RBI groundout.\nGunnar Nichols\nhad the most productive day out of the bullpen, tossing 3.1 innings with one hit allowed and three runs.\nCarson Boesel\nand\nJack Wade\nboth pitched in relief of\nHayden Lewis\nwho made the start on Sunday.\nThe Huskies will look to bounce back on Tuesday at Pepperdine. First pitch is scheduled for 1:35 p.m. in Malibu with the game broadcast on ESPN+.\nDAWG BITES\nJackson Hotchkiss\nchipped in a multi-home run game on Sunday\nHe now leads the team with six home runs despite only making 12 starts this season\nHotchkiss paces the team in home runs (6), doubles (6), is second in total bases (44), and third in total hits (20)\nHe also leads the team in batting average (.455), slugging (1.000), and on base percentage (.500)\nMic Paul\nhit Washington's ninth triple of the season, the 10\nth\nmost in the NCAA",
